sequences

Interface Sequence

  • All Known Subinterfaces:
    MassSequence
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    FastaSequence, FastaSequences, GenomicFastaSequence, ProteinFastaSequence, ProteinFastaSequences

    public interface Sequence
    Interface allowing access to sequence of characters. This abstract both access to elements in the sequence as Characters (in original form) and Bytes (in encoded form).
    Author:
    jung

      • getAlphabet

        java.util.Collection<java.lang.Character> getAlphabet()
        Return the alphabet set of this sequence as a Set of characters.
        Returns:
        the set of characters representing the alphabet

      • getAlphabetAsBytes

        java.util.Set<java.lang.Byte> getAlphabetAsBytes()
        Return the set of bytes that are valid for sequence. This is the alphabet set in the form of bytes (including the terminator character, but excluding un-encodable characters).
        Returns:
        the byte alphabet set

      • getAlphabetSize

        int getAlphabetSize()
        Returns the number of letters in the alphabet of this database.
        Returns:
        the alphabet size including the terminator character.

      • getAnnotation

        java.lang.String getAnnotation(long position)
        Get the annotation corresponds to the given position. Annotation can be any string. For example, if the object represented is a fasta file, annotation will be the lines start with ">".
        Parameters:
        position - the position to query. Annotations are mapped to certain ranges of the sequence indices, so this function will return the annotation for the subsequence that falls within this range
        Returns:
        the annotation string corresponds to the given position.

      • getByteAt

        byte getByteAt(long position)
        Get the encoded byte sequence at a given position. No error checking for boundaries is required.
        Parameters:
        position - the position to query.
        Returns:
        the byte at a given position.

      • getBytes

        byte[] getBytes(int start,
              int end)
        Get a slice of the sequence as a byte array representation.
        Parameters:
        start - the start index
        end - the end index (exclusive)
        Returns:
        the byte array of the slice

      • getCharAt

        char getCharAt(long position)
        Retrieve the original character in the sequence at the given position. No error checking for boundaries is required.
        Parameters:
        position - the location of the interested character.
        Returns:
        the character at the given position.

      • getId

        int getId()
        Get the unique identified for this sequence.
        Returns:
        the unique identifier used for the suffix array to verified that the tree was built on the same sequence.

      • getMatchingEntry

        java.lang.String getMatchingEntry(long position)
        Get the complete entry that corresponds to the given position. A chunk is a contiguous sequence that shares an annotation (e.g. Protein).
        Parameters:
        position - the position to query.
        Returns:
        the entry as a string corresponds to the given position.

      • getMatchingEntry

        java.lang.String getMatchingEntry(java.lang.String name)
        Get the complete entry that corresponds to the given fasta entry header. A chunk is a contiguous sequence that shares an annotation (e.g. Protein).
        Parameters:
        name - the header of the fasta entrry.
        Returns:
        the entry as a string.

      • getSize

        long getSize()
        The size of this sequence. All indexes [0, getSize()) should have valid characters.

        Returns:

      • toByte

        byte toByte(char c)
        Translates the given character to the binary representation.
        Parameters:
        c - the character to convert.
        Returns:
        the binary representation if available, but this might fail if the character is not in the alphabet.

      • toChar

        char toChar(byte b)
        Take a byte and reverse translate it to the original string representation. Note that some bytes might represent more than one character. An arbitrary character is returned. To find out what the original char was, the getCharAt method should be called instead
        Parameters:
        b - the byte.
        Returns:
        the String representation of the given byte.

        Returns:
